.TITLE "git masterclass"

.DIV "1. THE CORE CONCEPT"
Git is a **Distributed Version Control System**. This means every developer has a full copy of the project history on their own machine. It is fast, reliable, and designed to handle everything from small projects to the Linux kernel.

.DIV "2. THE WORKFLOW"
The standard git workflow follows these steps:

**Step A: Modify Files**
You make changes to your code in the __working directory__.

**Step B: Stage Changes**
You use `git add` to tell git which changes you want to include in your next snapshot.

**Step C: Commit**
You use `git commit` to permanently store that snapshot in your local history.

.DIV "3. BRANCHING"
Branches are the "killer feature" of git. They are incredibly lightweight.

To create a new branch:
**git branch feature-name**

To switch to that branch:
**git switch feature-name**

Working on a branch allows you to experiment without breaking the __main__ code. When you are done, you can merge your work back.

.DIV "4. MERGING"
Merging combines work from two different branches.

1. Switch to the branch you want to merge *into* (usually main).
2. Run: **git merge feature-name**

If two people changed the same line, you might get a __merge conflict__. Don't panic! Git will mark the file, and you just need to choose which version to keep.

.DIV "5. REMOTE REPOS"
To collaborate, you connect your local repo to a service like GitHub.

**origin** is the default name for your remote server.
**upstream** is often used for the original repo you "forked" from.

Commands:
- `git fetch`: Pull data from remote but don't merge it.
- `git pull`: Fetch and merge in one go.
- `git push`: Send your local commits to the server.

.DIV "6. UNDOING THINGS"
Mistakes happen. Git has several ways to fix them:

**git restore <file>**
Discards changes in your working directory that haven't been staged yet.

**git reset --soft HEAD~1**
Undo the last commit but keep your changes in the staging area.

**git commit --amend**
Change the message or contents of the very last commit you made.

.DIV "7. STASHING"
If you need to switch branches but aren't ready to commit, you can "hide" your changes:

**git stash**
This clears your working directory and saves changes on a "stack".

**git stash pop**
This brings your hidden changes back so you can continue working.

.DIV "8. SUMMARY"
Mastering git takes time. Focus on the basics first:
- Always __git status__ before you act.
- Write clear, present-tense commit messages.
- Commit often, but only when the code works!
- Don't be afraid to experiment with branches.

Happy coding!
